awd_titl_txt: Does Access to Computing Education Improve Equity? Identifying Promising Practices and Existing Barriers for Broadening Participation among Underrepresented Students in California
awd_abstract_narration:
Does Access to Computing Education Improve Equity?  To address the underrepresentation of women and people of color in computing education and careers, national, state, and local efforts have ramped up to expand access to computer science education at the secondary school level and provide the skills all students need to participate in the technology-driven economy.  This study examines the relationship between the expansion of access to computing education course offerings and the enrollment, success, and persistence in computing course sequences among underrepresented students across the state of California. This study examines whether current broadening participation in computing initiatives are improving racial and gender equity in computing at the high school level. The work informs strategies for effectively improving computing education outcomes among underrepresented people of color and women of all kinds and broadening the talent pool of the future U.S. computing workforce.
 
This study focuses in California, examining statewide data trends and data across three school districts that have implemented computer science course expansion efforts-- Oakland, Los Angeles and San Francisco. This multiyear longitudinal study of computing course availability, student enrollment/participation, student success, and persistence in computing courses: (a) Identifies successful interventions and existing challenges in broadening participation and closing equity gaps in computing, and (b) Identifies the demographic, academic, and curricular factors that are predictive of short- and long-term computing outcomes across student populations. This work informs, refines, and improves ongoing district and state-level computer science expansion plans through an intentional process of continual improvement, and produces empirical and theoretical findings to inform efforts to broaden participation in K-12 computing education.

por.por_cntn:
This longitudinal research project aimed to examine access, participation, and success in K-12 computer science education across the state of California, and in three focal districts (Oakland Unified, Los Angeles Unified, and San Francisco Unified) to explore progress towards broadening participation and closing equity gaps by race, gender, income, and zip code. Key accomplishments include: 

  • Published the report, Computer Science in California’s Schools: An Analysis of Access, Enrollment and Equity (June, 2019), providing 4 years of trend data demonstrating that while overall access to computer science courses has increased, racial and gender equity gaps persist. The report concluded with a set of comprehensive recommendations. 

  • Published an updated report, The California Computer Science Access Report (September, 2021), providing 5 years of trend data demonstrating similar increases in overall statewide access, and increases in specific districts, but persistent racial and gender equity gaps in access to computer science courses in California. 

  • Utilized disparate sources of data in California to create a searchable data tool, accessible to educators, policymakers, parents, and advocates to understand the CS landscape in their county/district, and explore gaps of access and equity. The data tool has been widely disseminated to educators, administrators, policymakers and citizens across the state of California, and has been instrumental in supporting efforts to advocate for computer science at the state, city, district, and school level. 

  • Disseminated data, research, and recommendations to diverse audiences including: computer science teachers; school counselors; district administrators; parents; state policymakers; education advocates; researchers; and other practitioners and partners at conferences, webinars, meetings, and briefings. 

  • Integrated the research into the CSforCA coalition’s effort to create a statewide, multi-stakeholder coalition advocating for, and implementing rigorous computer science education across the state. 

 

This project contributed significantly to the field of broadening participation in computing by demonstrating ways in which efforts to increase access to computer science across one of the most populous and diverse states in the country were successful, and where challenges in equitable access to computer science remain. In particular, challenges were identified at the district and state level that were impediments towards building robust, rigorous, and diverse computer science educational pathways--including teacher preparation and development, school funding allocations, mandates and accountability--among others. This evidence can (a) contribute to the evidence base on effective strategies for broadening participation in computing and (b) inform future strategies at the national, state, and local level for effectively improving computing education and, in particular improving outcomes among groups most underrepresented in computing.
